## Part 6 — Knowledge Relationships

### 6.1 Knowledge ↔ Observation

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Relationship** | Knowledge is derived from Observations. Observations are the foundational evidence from which Knowledge is built. |
| **Direction** | Observation → Knowledge (Observations support Knowledge derivation) AND Knowledge → Observation (Knowledge references Observations during explanation). |
| **Cardinality** | A Knowledge item traces to multiple Observations. An Observation may support multiple Knowledge items. |
| **Cognitive significance** | This is the most fundamental Knowledge relationship. Knowledge without Observation support is speculation. |

### 6.2 Knowledge ↔ Pattern

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Relationship** | Knowledge is often derived from Pattern promotion. Validated Patterns become Knowledge. |
| **Direction** | Pattern → Knowledge (promoted Pattern generates Knowledge) AND Knowledge → Pattern (Knowledge references originating Patterns). |
| **Cardinality** | A Knowledge item may be derived from one or more Patterns. A Pattern may generate one or more Knowledge items. |
| **Cognitive significance** | This relationship is the bridge from pattern discovery to validated understanding. |

### 6.3 Knowledge ↔ Evidence

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Relationship** | Every piece of Knowledge must be supported by Evidence. Evidence justifies Knowledge. |
| **Direction** | Evidence → Knowledge (Evidence supports Knowledge) AND Knowledge → Evidence (Knowledge references supporting Evidence). |
| **Cardinality** | A Knowledge item is supported by multiple Evidence items. An Evidence item may support multiple Knowledge items. |
| **Cognitive significance** | This relationship implements Constitution Article 5 (Knowledge Is Earned). Knowledge without Evidence is not Knowledge. |

### 6.4 Knowledge ↔ Memory

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Relationship** | Knowledge is stored in Memory (Knowledge Memory / Long-Term Memory). Memory is the container that preserves Knowledge across time. |
| **Direction** | Knowledge → Memory (Knowledge is stored in Memory) AND Memory → Knowledge (Memory enables Knowledge retrieval). |
| **Cardinality** | All Knowledge exists in Memory. Not all Memory is Knowledge. |
| **Cognitive significance** | This relationship distinguishes Knowledge from other cognitive artifacts. Knowledge is Memory that has passed validation. |

### 6.5 Knowledge ↔ Learning

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Relationship** | Learning produces Knowledge. Knowledge enables further Learning. The relationship is a continuous cycle. |
| **Direction** | Learning → Knowledge (Learning generates Knowledge) AND Knowledge → Learning (Knowledge informs what the system learns next). |
| **Cardinality** | A Learning event may produce multiple Knowledge items. Knowledge may inform multiple Learning events. |
| **Cognitive significance** | This relationship is the engine of cumulative intelligence. Each cycle of Learning produces Knowledge that makes the next cycle smarter. |

### 6.6 Knowledge ↔ Decision

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Relationship** | Knowledge informs Decisions. Decisions produce outcomes that generate Learning, which produces new Knowledge. |
| **Direction** | Knowledge → Decision (Knowledge informs decision-making) AND Decision → Knowledge (through Learning). |
| **Cardinality** | A Decision may reference multiple Knowledge items. Knowledge may inform multiple Decisions. |
| **Cognitive significance** | This relationship ensures that decisions are grounded in validated understanding. Decisions without Knowledge are guesses. |

### 6.7 Knowledge ↔ Recommendation

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Relationship** | Knowledge is the foundation of every Recommendation. The system recommends actions based on what it knows. |
| **Direction** | Knowledge → Recommendation (Knowledge supports Recommendation generation). |
| **Cardinality** | A Recommendation may reference multiple Knowledge items. Knowledge may support multiple Recommendations. |
| **Cognitive significance** | This relationship implements Product Principle 10 (Every Recommendation Has a Reason) and Product Principle 7 (Explain Before Recommend). |

### 6.8 Knowledge ↔ Narrative

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Relationship** | Knowledge provides the content for Narratives. Narratives communicate Knowledge to the Owner. |
| **Direction** | Knowledge → Narrative (Knowledge provides narrative raw material). |
| **Cardinality** | A Narrative may reference multiple Knowledge items. Knowledge may appear in multiple Narratives. |
| **Cognitive significance** | This relationship connects validated understanding (Knowledge) to meaningful communication (Narrative). Narratives without Knowledge are stories. |

### 6.9 Knowledge ↔ Confidence

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Relationship** | Every piece of Knowledge has a confidence value. Confidence determines how much influence Knowledge has on reasoning. |
| **Direction** | Knowledge has Confidence (confidence is a property of Knowledge). Confidence determines Knowledge influence. |
| **Cardinality** | Every Knowledge item has exactly one confidence value that evolves over time. |
| **Cognitive significance** | Confidence is how Knowledge calibrates its own influence. High-confidence Knowledge drives reasoning; low-confidence Knowledge is used cautiously. |

### 6.10 Knowledge ↔ Business Pulse

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Relationship** | Knowledge informs Business Pulse understanding. Business Pulse context modulates how Knowledge is applied. |
| **Direction** | Knowledge → Business Pulse (Knowledge provides baseline for Pulse assessment) AND Business Pulse → Knowledge (Pulse context modulates Knowledge application). |
| **Cardinality** | All Knowledge contributes to Business Pulse understanding. Business Pulse influences all Knowledge application during its period. |
| **Cognitive significance** | This relationship ensures that Knowledge is applied appropriately for the current business conditions. The same Knowledge may be applied differently during normal Pulse versus anomalous Pulse. |

### 6.11 Knowledge ↔ Owner

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Relationship** | Knowledge about the Owner (preferences, decision patterns, values) enables personalized interaction. Owner feedback validates or corrects Knowledge. |
| **Direction** | Knowledge → Owner (Knowledge informs Owner interaction) AND Owner → Knowledge (Owner feedback validates or corrects Knowledge). |
| **Cardinality** | Multiple Knowledge items relate to a single Owner. Owner feedback may affect multiple Knowledge items. |
| **Cognitive significance** | This relationship implements Product Principle 24 (The Owner is always right about their business). Owner feedback is the highest-priority validation signal. |

### 6.12 Knowledge ↔ Restaurant

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Relationship** | Knowledge about a specific Restaurant enables personalized service. Restaurant-specific Knowledge is isolated to that Restaurant. |
| **Direction** | Knowledge → Restaurant (Knowledge informs Restaurant understanding) AND Restaurant → Knowledge (Restaurant data generates Knowledge). |
| **Cardinality** | Multiple Knowledge items relate to a single Restaurant. A Restaurant generates multiple Knowledge items. |
| **Cognitive significance** | This relationship implements business isolation. Knowledge from one Restaurant does not automatically apply to another. |

### 6.13 Knowledge ↔ Strategy

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Relationship** | Strategic Knowledge informs long-term direction. Operational Knowledge informs strategic decisions through aggregation. |
| **Direction** | Strategic Knowledge → Strategy (Knowledge informs strategic direction) AND Strategy → Knowledge (strategic decisions produce Knowledge through outcomes). |
| **Cardinality** | Multiple Knowledge items contribute to strategic understanding. Strategic decisions produce new Knowledge. |
| **Cognitive significance** | This relationship connects day-to-day understanding to long-term direction. |

### 6.14 Knowledge ↔ Goals

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Relationship** | Knowledge informs goal setting (what is achievable) and goal progress tracking (how the business is tracking against targets). |
| **Direction** | Knowledge → Goals (Knowledge informs realistic goal setting) AND Goals → Knowledge (goal outcomes produce Knowledge). |
| **Cardinality** | Multiple Knowledge items inform a single goal. Goal outcomes produce one or more Knowledge items. |
| **Cognitive significance** | This relationship ensures that goals are grounded in validated understanding. Goals without Knowledge are wishes. |

### 6.15 Knowledge ↔ Context

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Relationship** | Knowledge is context-dependent. The same Knowledge may apply differently in different contexts. Context determines which Knowledge is relevant. |
| **Direction** | Knowledge → Context (Knowledge about context factors) AND Context → Knowledge (context constrains Knowledge application). |
| **Cardinality** | Knowledge may be valid in multiple contexts. A context may activate multiple Knowledge items. |
| **Cognitive significance** | This relationship implements context-aware reasoning. Knowledge is never applied without context consideration. |

### 6.16 Knowledge ↔ Intelligence

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Relationship** | Knowledge is the input to Intelligence. Intelligence is the application of Knowledge to novel situations. |
| **Direction** | Knowledge → Intelligence (Knowledge enables intelligent reasoning) AND Intelligence → Knowledge (intelligent reasoning generates new Knowledge). |
| **Cardinality** | All Knowledge feeds Intelligence. Intelligence produces new Knowledge through Learning. |
| **Cognitive significance** | This relationship defines the architecture of cognition. Knowledge is what the system knows. Intelligence is what the system does with what it knows. |

