## Part 4 — Attention Classification

### 4.1 Classification Model

Every Attention allocation belongs to exactly one primary category and may belong to zero or more secondary categories.

#### Operational Attention

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | Attention allocated to day-to-day business operations: sales transactions, service times, inventory movements, staff scheduling, order processing. |
| **Purpose** | Enables operational awareness and real-time response. |
| **Priority basis** | Impact on immediate operations. |
| **Typical urgency** | Medium-High. Operational issues degrade quickly. |
| **Interruptibility** | Can be interrupted by Emergency, Owner, or Business Pulse Attention. |

#### Strategic Attention

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | Attention allocated to long-term business direction: market trends, competitive analysis, strategic planning, goal progress, investment decisions. |
| **Purpose** | Enables long-term reasoning and strategic alignment. |
| **Priority basis** | Alignment with business goals. |
| **Typical urgency** | Low-Medium. Strategic issues develop over time. |
| **Interruptibility** | Can be interrupted by any higher-urgency category. |

#### Emergency Attention

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | Attention allocated to events that threaten business continuity or require immediate action: equipment failure, safety incident, critical system outage, health emergency. |
| **Purpose** | Enables immediate response to threats. |
| **Priority basis** | Threat level. |
| **Typical urgency** | Critical. |
| **Interruptibility** | Cannot be interrupted by any category except higher-severity Emergency. Highest priority. |

#### Owner Attention

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | Attention allocated to stimuli originating from the Owner: Owner questions, Owner commands, Owner feedback, Owner preferences. |
| **Purpose** | Enables responsive interaction with the Owner. |
| **Priority basis** | Owner's explicit or implicit priority. |
| **Typical urgency** | Variable (determined by Owner's communication). |
| **Interruptibility** | Can interrupt most categories. Owner Attention has override capability. |

#### Business Pulse Attention

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | Attention allocated to Business Pulse monitoring: health state changes, Pulse degradation, Pulse recovery, anomaly detection in Pulse metrics. |
| **Purpose** | Enables Pulse-aware cognitive processing. |
| **Priority basis** | Pulse change magnitude. |
| **Typical urgency** | Medium. Pulse changes are early indicators. |
| **Interruptibility** | Can be interrupted by Emergency and Owner Attention. |

#### Learning Attention

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | Attention allocated to learning opportunities: outcome analysis, contradiction resolution, pattern validation, Knowledge extraction. |
| **Purpose** | Enables continuous improvement through learning. |
| **Priority basis** | Learning value. |
| **Typical urgency** | Low-Medium. Learning is valuable but rarely urgent. |
| **Interruptibility** | Can be interrupted by most categories. Learning is important but not time-sensitive. |

#### Prediction Attention

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | Attention allocated to prediction monitoring: forecast accuracy tracking, prediction deviation detection, confidence drift in predictions. |
| **Purpose** | Enables the system to monitor how well its predictions match reality. |
| **Priority basis** | Prediction deviation magnitude. |
| **Typical urgency** | Medium. Prediction deviations are early warning signals. |
| **Interruptibility** | Can be interrupted by Emergency, Owner, and Operational Attention. |

#### Reflection Attention

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | Attention allocated to self-assessment: cognitive health review, attention allocation audit, memory quality check, Knowledge consistency verification. |
| **Purpose** | Enables meta-cognitive self-evaluation. |
| **Priority basis** | Time since last reflection. Identified issues. |
| **Typical urgency** | Low. Reflection is scheduled, not event-driven. |
| **Interruptibility** | Can be interrupted by any category. Scheduled reflection yields to operational needs. |

#### Anomaly Attention

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | Attention allocated to anomalous events: unexpected patterns, outliers, threshold violations, deviation from established baselines. |
| **Purpose** | Enables detection and investigation of anomalies. |
| **Priority basis** | Anomaly magnitude and potential impact. |
| **Typical urgency** | Medium-High. Anomalies may indicate emerging problems. |
| **Interruptibility** | Can interrupt Operational and Background Attention. Interrupted by Emergency and Owner. |

#### Risk Attention

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | Attention allocated to risk monitoring: identified risk factors, risk threshold approaches, risk mitigation status, emerging risks. |
| **Purpose** | Enables proactive risk management. |
| **Priority basis** | Risk level and proximity. |
| **Typical urgency** | Medium. Risks are monitored continuously. |
| **Interruptibility** | Can be interrupted by Emergency, Owner, and Anomaly. |

#### Goal Attention

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | Attention allocated to goal progress: milestone tracking, goal deviation, goal achievement, goal redefinition. |
| **Purpose** | Enables goal-aligned cognitive processing and progress awareness. |
| **Priority basis** | Goal criticality and proximity. |
| **Typical urgency** | Low-Medium. Goals are tracked over extended periods. |
| **Interruptibility** | Can be interrupted by Operational and Emergency categories. |

#### Planning Attention

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | Attention allocated to planning activities: resource planning, capacity planning, menu planning, promotion planning, seasonal preparation. |
| **Purpose** | Enables proactive planning rather than reactive response. |
| **Priority basis** | Planning horizon proximity. |
| **Typical urgency** | Variable. Depends on planning deadline. |
| **Interruptibility** | Can be interrupted by most operational categories. |

#### Conversation Attention

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | Attention allocated to communication with the Owner: answering questions, providing explanations, discussing recommendations, receiving feedback. |
| **Purpose** | Enables interactive dialogue with the Owner. |
| **Priority basis** | Owner's expressed need. |
| **Typical urgency** | Variable (determined by Owner). |
| **Interruptibility** | Owner Conversation cannot be interrupted by non-emergency categories. |

#### External Attention

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | Attention allocated to external factors: weather, events, holidays, competitor activity, economic indicators, regulatory changes. |
| **Purpose** | Enables context-aware cognition that incorporates external conditions. |
| **Priority basis** | External factor impact potential. |
| **Typical urgency** | Variable. Depends on external event proximity. |
| **Interruptibility** | Can be interrupted by Internal and Emergency categories. |

#### Internal Attention

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | Attention allocated to the system's own cognitive processes: memory health, Knowledge quality, reasoning consistency, Learning extraction, cognitive parameter adjustment. |
| **Purpose** | Enables self-monitoring and self-maintenance. |
| **Priority basis** | Cognitive health indicators. |
| **Typical urgency** | Low-Medium. Self-monitoring is background work. |
| **Interruptibility** | Can be interrupted by any category. |

#### Composite Attention

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | Attention synthesized from multiple lower-level Attention items. A unified allocation built from contributing parts — e.g., a "restaurant health decline" that combines Operational, Anomaly, and Risk Attention. |
| **Purpose** | Enables higher-order Attention that aggregates multiple signals. |
| **Priority basis** | Aggregated score from component Attention items. |
| **Typical urgency** | Determined by highest-urgency component. |
| **Interruptibility** | Composite Attention is interrupted when all components are resolved. |

### 4.2 Classification Principles

1. **Every Attention allocation has exactly one primary category.**
2. **An Attention allocation may have multiple secondary categories.**
3. **Category determines priority weighting and interrupt behavior.**
4. **Category may evolve** as the stimulus is better understood.
5. **Composite Attention aggregates multiple lower-level allocations.**

