## Part 10 — Reasoning Failure Modes

### 10.1 Failure Mode Framework

Every failure mode follows the same structure: Definition, Symptoms, Root Cause, Detection, Severity, Recovery, Prevention.

#### Circular Reasoning

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | The reasoning process uses its conclusion as a premise. A proves B because of C, but C assumes B. |
| **Symptoms** | Reasoning chain loops back on itself. No new information is introduced. The system appears to be going in circles. |
| **Root cause** | (1) Missing external inputs. (2) Insufficient Knowledge. (3) Inadequate consistency checking. (4) Reasoning process trapped in a cycle. |
| **Detection** | The reasoning graph contains a cycle. A premise references a conclusion. |
| **Severity** | Critical — circular reasoning is not reasoning. It is self-deception. |
| **Recovery** | Identify the circular dependency. Break the cycle by requiring an external input. If no external input is available, flag the reasoning as incomplete. |
| **Prevention** | Implement cycle detection in consistency checking. Require at least one external input per reasoning step. |

#### Confirmation Bias

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | The reasoning process favors evidence and Knowledge that confirms its preferred conclusion while ignoring or discounting contradicting evidence. |
| **Symptoms** | All evidence supports the conclusion. Contradicting evidence is absent or dismissed. Alternatives are not genuinely considered. |
| **Root cause** | (1) Hypothesis generated before evidence gathered. (2) Unequal weighting of confirming vs. disconfirming evidence. (3) Tunnel vision in evidence retrieval. |
| **Detection** | Evidence distribution is skewed toward confirming evidence. Disconfirming evidence exists but is not referenced. |
| **Severity** | High — leads to systematically wrong conclusions. |
| **Recovery** | Force retrieval of disconfirming evidence. Re-evaluate evidence weighting. Generate counter-hypotheses. |
| **Prevention** | Always retrieve disconfirming evidence. Implement balanced evidence retrieval policy. Force alternative generation before evaluation. |

#### Tunnel Reasoning

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | The reasoning process narrows its focus too early, considering only one explanation or approach and ignoring alternatives. |
| **Symptoms** | Single hypothesis from the start. No genuine alternatives. Conclusion is predetermined. Surface-level analysis. |
| **Root cause** | (1) Premature hypothesis commitment. (2) Overconfidence in initial assessment. (3) Time pressure causing early narrowing. |
| **Detection** | Alternative count is below minimum. All alternatives are variations of the same approach. |
| **Severity** | High — leads to missed solutions and overlooked risks. |
| **Recovery** | Force generation of additional alternatives. Challenge the initial hypothesis. |
| **Prevention** | Enforce minimum alternative count. Implement mandatory alternative generation phase. |

#### Weak Evidence

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | The reasoning process relies on evidence that is insufficient, unreliable, or irrelevant to support its conclusion. |
| **Symptoms** | Conclusion is not supported by evidence quality. Evidence does not adequately address the question. Evidence is outdated or from unreliable sources. |
| **Root cause** | (1) Evidence not evaluated for quality. (2) Evidence sufficiency not assessed. (3) Conclusion over-extrapolated from limited evidence. |
| **Detection** | Evidence-to-conclusion gap. Confidence exceeds what evidence supports. |
| **Severity** | Medium-High — conclusions are unsupported. |
| **Recovery** | Identify evidence gaps. Retrieve better evidence. Reduce confidence to match evidence strength. |
| **Prevention** | Implement evidence sufficiency check. Calibrate confidence to evidence quality. |

#### Premature Conclusion

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | The reasoning process reaches a conclusion before sufficient evidence, Knowledge, or analysis is available. |
| **Symptoms** | Short reasoning duration. Few stages completed. Conclusion reached in Evidence Gathering or earlier. |
| **Root cause** | (1) Time pressure. (2) Overconfidence. (3) Owner impatience. (4) System急于满足. |
| **Detection** | Lifecycle duration significantly shorter than expected for the reasoning type. |
| **Severity** | Medium — conclusions may be wrong but are not necessarily wrong. |
| **Recovery** | Return to appropriate lifecycle stage. Complete the analysis. If time pressure was the cause, flag time-pressure reasoning. |
| **Prevention** | Enforce minimum stage durations per reasoning type. Implement gate checks at each stage transition. |

#### Incomplete Context

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | The reasoning process does not have sufficient context to reach a valid conclusion. Critical contextual factors are missing. |
| **Symptoms** | Conclusion does not account for relevant conditions. The Owner identifies missing context. Reasoning is inappropriate for the situation. |
| **Root cause** | (1) Context not retrieved. (2) Context retrieval failed. (3) Relevant context factors not known to the system. |
| **Detection** | Context completeness check fails. Missing context factors identified. |
| **Severity** | High — context-blind reasoning produces context-blind conclusions. |
| **Recovery** | Retrieve missing context. Re-evaluate reasoning with complete context. If context cannot be retrieved, flag as incomplete context reasoning. |
| **Prevention** | Implement context completeness checklist per reasoning type. Require context validation before proceeding. |

#### False Assumption

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | The reasoning process makes an assumption that is incorrect, and the conclusion depends on this assumption. |
| **Symptoms** | Conclusion is valid given assumptions, but assumptions do not match reality. |
| **Root cause** | (1) Assumption not validated. (2) Assumption inherited from unreliable source. (3) Assumption was true when made but has since changed. |
| **Detection** | Assumption sensitivity analysis reveals conclusion depends on unverified assumption. |
| **Severity** | High — false assumptions propagate through the entire reasoning chain. |
| **Recovery** | Identify the false assumption. Validate or correct it. Re-run reasoning with corrected assumption. |
| **Prevention** | Flag all assumptions. Distinguish verified from unverified assumptions. Test key assumptions. |

#### Knowledge Conflict

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | The reasoning process encounters conflicting Knowledge items and does not resolve the conflict before proceeding. |
| **Symptoms** | Reasoning uses contradictory Knowledge. Conclusion depends on one Knowledge item while ignoring a conflicting one. |
| **Root cause** | (1) Knowledge conflict not detected. (2) Knowledge conflict detected but not resolved. (3) Knowledge System has unresolved conflict. |
| **Detection** | Conflicting Knowledge items are both referenced. |
| **Severity** | Critical — reasoning is built on contradictory foundations. |
| **Recovery** | Resolve Knowledge conflict according to Knowledge System rules. If unresolvable, flag for Learning and proceed with both perspectives. |
| **Prevention** | Implement Knowledge conflict detection in retrieval phase. Do not proceed with unresolved conflicts. |

#### Overconfidence

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | The reasoning process expresses higher confidence than the evidence and Knowledge support. |
| **Symptoms** | High confidence with weak evidence. Recommendation presented as certain when it is not. |
| **Root cause** | (1) Confidence estimation error. (2) Evidence quality overestimated. (3) Knowledge completeness overestimated. (4) Unconscious bias. |
| **Detection** | Confidence exceeds evidence strength. Historical accuracy at similar confidence levels is lower than expected. |
| **Severity** | High — leads to decisions based on false certainty. |
| **Recovery** | Recalibrate confidence. Identify sources of overestimation. |
| **Prevention** | Implement confidence calibration tracking. Compare confidence to actual correctness over time. |

#### Underconfidence

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | The reasoning process expresses lower confidence than the evidence and Knowledge support. |
| **Symptoms** | Low confidence despite strong evidence. Recommendation presented hesitantly when it could be confident. Owner may discount valid recommendations. |
| **Root cause** | (1) Confidence estimation error. (2) Evidence quality underestimated. (3) Excessive caution. (4) Past errors causing overcorrection. |
| **Detection** | Confidence is lower than evidence strength warrants. Historical accuracy at similar confidence levels is higher than expected. |
| **Severity** | Medium — reduces the impact of valid recommendations. |
| **Recovery** | Recalibrate confidence. Review evidence strength. |
| **Prevention** | Implement confidence calibration tracking. Compare confidence to actual correctness. |

#### Reasoning Collapse

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | The reasoning process fails to produce any conclusion or recommendation. The system cannot complete the reasoning lifecycle. |
| **Symptoms** | Reasoning stalls at a stage. Repeated stage re-entries. No recommendation produced. Process exceeds maximum duration. |
| **Root cause** | (1) Insufficient inputs. (2) Unresolvable contradictions. (3) No alternative survives constraints. (4) Confidence never reaches threshold. |
| **Detection** | Lifecycle duration exceeds maximum with no completion in sight. |
| **Severity** | Critical — the system cannot produce understanding. |
| **Recovery** | Escalate. Identify the blocking issue. If no alternative survives constraints, escalate constraint conflict. If contradictions cannot be resolved, present both sides. |
| **Prevention** | Implement reasoning collapse detection. Set maximum reasoning duration. Establish escalation path for blocked reasoning. |

#### Analysis Paralysis

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | The reasoning process continues analyzing indefinitely, generating more alternatives, more evidence, more tradeoffs, without reaching a conclusion. |
| **Symptoms** | Increasing number of alternatives. Diminishing returns per additional analysis. Never reaching recommendation. |
| **Root cause** | (1) Perfectionism. (2) Fear of wrong conclusion. (3) Insufficient stopping criteria. (4) No decision deadline. |
| **Detection** | Analysis-to-conclusion ratio is excessive. Alternatives increase without convergence. |
| **Severity** | Medium — delays decision but may produce better analysis in theory. |
| **Recovery** | Force conclusion. Impose deadline. Select best available alternative. |
| **Prevention** | Set maximum alternatives. Implement diminishing returns detection. Enforce decision deadlines. |

#### Recommendation Drift

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | The recommendation changes significantly as the reasoning process progresses, without new evidence or Knowledge to justify the change. |
| **Symptoms** | Final recommendation differs significantly from intermediate recommendations without clear justification. |
| **Root cause** | (1) Unstable inputs. (2) Inconsistent evaluation criteria. (3) Weight drift during tradeoff evaluation. |
| **Detection** | Comparison of intermediate recommendations across lifecycle shows significant variation without input changes. |
| **Severity** | Medium — indicates unstable reasoning. |
| **Recovery** | Identify the point of drift. Determine if new information justified the change. If not, stabilize evaluation criteria. |
| **Prevention** | Log intermediate recommendations. Implement drift detection. Freeze criteria during evaluation. |

#### Owner Misalignment

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | The reasoning process produces a recommendation that does not align with the Owner's goals, preferences, or values. |
| **Symptoms** | Owner rejects recommendation. Owner expresses surprise or disagreement. Recommendation ignores known Owner preferences. |
| **Root cause** | (1) Owner preferences not retrieved. (2) Owner preferences misinterpreted. (3) Reasoning prioritized other factors over Owner alignment. |
| **Detection** | Owner feedback indicates misalignment. |
| **Severity** | High — undermines trust in the system. |
| **Recovery** | Retrieve Owner preferences. Re-evaluate recommendation with Owner alignment as primary factor. Present corrected recommendation. |
| **Prevention** | Always retrieve latest Owner preferences. Include Owner alignment as mandatory evaluation criterion. |

#### Speculative Reasoning

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Definition** | The reasoning process goes beyond what evidence and Knowledge support, making leaps that are not justified. |
| **Symptoms** | Conclusions that are plausible but not supported. Gaps in the reasoning chain filled by speculation rather than evidence. |
| **Root cause** | (1) Insufficient evidence leading to gap-filling. (2) Overactive hypothesis generation. (3) Pressure to produce a conclusion. |
| **Detection** | Reasoning chain has gaps filled with unsupported statements. Confidence is higher than evidence supports. |
| **Severity** | High — speculation masquerading as reasoning. |
| **Recovery** | Identify speculative steps. Remove or flag them. Reduce confidence to reflect actual support. |
| **Prevention** | Flag reasoning chain gaps. Require evidence or Knowledge support for each step. |

### 10.2 Failure Mode Summary

| Mode | Severity | Detection Method | Recovery Speed | Business Impact |
|------|----------|------------------|----------------|-----------------|
| Circular Reasoning | Critical | Cycle detection | Slow | Invalid reasoning |
| Confirmation Bias | High | Evidence distribution | Medium | Systematic error |
| Tunnel Reasoning | High | Alternative count | Medium | Missed solutions |
| Weak Evidence | Medium-High | Evidence strength | Medium | Unsupported conclusions |
| Premature Conclusion | Medium | Stage duration | Fast | Potentially wrong |
| Incomplete Context | High | Context completeness | Medium | Context-blind results |
| False Assumption | High | Assumption sensitivity | Medium | Propagated error |
| Knowledge Conflict | Critical | Conflict detection | Slow | Contradictory foundation |
| Overconfidence | High | Confidence calibration | Medium | False certainty |
| Underconfidence | Medium | Confidence calibration | Medium | Reduced impact |
| Reasoning Collapse | Critical | Lifecycle monitoring | Slow | No output |
| Analysis Paralysis | Medium | Analysis ratio | Fast | Delayed output |
| Recommendation Drift | Medium | Recommendation tracking | Medium | Unstable output |
| Owner Misalignment | High | Owner feedback | Medium | Trust erosion |
| Speculative Reasoning | High | Reasoning chain audit | Medium | Unsupported conclusions |

